{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b6fb4c22-1217-4354-8fdf-a5c6356937a2","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2. In modern MSTest (v3+), `TestContext` is injected via the constructor, and you can combine it with `[ClassInitialize]`/`[TestInitialize]` for async setup. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // Constructor injection for TestContext (sync init goes here)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // synchronous setup work\n    }\n\n    // Async class-level init (runs once per class)\n    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static async Task ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        // async one-time setup (e.g., spin up shared resource)\n        await Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    // Async per-test init\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task TestInit()\n    {\n        // async per-test setup (e.g., seed database)\n        await Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_testContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor** — use for synchronous DI and storing `TestContext`.\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — use for async per-test setup (`async Task`).\n- **`[ClassInitialize]`** — use for async one-time class setup (must be `static`).\n- Constructor injection of `TestContext` replaced the property-setter pattern from MSTest v1/v2.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"36483f82-4dbe-4293-9930-bf047697ac71","outputTokens":395,"requestId":"E442:29262A:343AD59:39B319F:6A02FB74"},"id":"0e25a57e-8aef-4d6a-9a27-4b50419ed31f","timestamp":"2026-05-12T10:05:55.040Z","parentId":"93f762d7-b2e8-4e23-a76e-6c226c75968c"}
